April 8, 1950
Dear Jack, 
Just a brief note of "thanks" for putting me wise to (Writers of My Generation) in Eileen Garrett's splendid magazine. 
I think it "must" reading for every dreamy-eyed young writer and especially those knocking themselves out in journalism schools and the like. Already, I am aware that writing is sheer drudgery, which requires a powerful emotional drive, as well as capacity for self-discipline.  
It has become a habit on my part, while browsing in bookshops to scan searchingly for 'The Disinherited.' Though I have read it, I still pursue it as an addition to my collection. 
Excuse pen -- my typewriter is once again gathering dust in its second home; "Ye ole faithful damn dealer." My sightseeing tour in the role of an itinerant worker has me now on my 60th job (since '45) as a sewing machine mechanic apprentice. Add to this, employment as a steel worker, railroad worker, factory worker, dish washer, advertising and, and, and -- all with the idea, that the problem in writing isn't so much "how?" but "what?" what to write about.
Muriel is going to purchase 'Sam Patch' in San Fan. She's richer than I! Do you think the Conroy's have any way with money--or are they all Wednesday's Children?
Gratefully, 
Tom

Jack, 
This is a personal letter from Muriel -- But thought you might see, or like seeing where Algren rates. Trying to sell us -- Conroy -- And succeed in selling Nelson.
Tom Conroy (no relation)

A new magazine with a spirit for the type of material I like to write, is in the making out your way. Clear-views. 
My novel Let Down is near completion. The writing is nothing to cause Angren unrest, for if I write for another sixty years I still will be out of his league. 
Speaking of Midland Honor -- The same cleptomaniac [sic] who pilfered your book of verse, lifted my one and only copy of Midland Humor. I wonder if her record at the public library is as successful. Every time that I see empty space in a book case I bring to mind that red-head. 
A friend of mine (A student at Syracuse) is attempting to stage one of my plays there. Has Jas. Light, perhaps, already informed you of this?
"Old soldiers never die." I'm not an old soldier, but I nearly died when "Mac" declared: "These men were mine." Making reference to those boys from Maywood, who blood-soaked the shores of Bataan. 
Sincerely
Tom

Tom Conroy
2500 W. Flournoy St., 
Chicago I2, Illinois

            Jack Conroy
            6012 So. Green St,. 
            Chicago, Illinois

Dear Jack, 
Please forgive my failure to attend those socials you were so kind to invite me to. Due to the wounds of the sheer drudgery of struggling writing, I would have made a disgraceful appearance. It is better for the name of Conroy I failed to show. I have been winning a great of publicity and kinds words, but no money. I 'm just stuck with a dream of being a playwright -- against a group of merciless playreaders and producers. Oh--But you know all this Jack!
Soon as I once more an back on my feet, I will visit the house of complexes. This summer, Muriel comes to town and wants to meet you. My novel is coming along at a nice pace
Tom
